# Headless CLI — **mandatory**

## A. External AI (Claude / Codex / Gemini / Qwen)

When work is delegated to **Claude Code**, **OpenAI Codex**, **Gemini CLI**, or **Qwen Code**, execution **must** use **non-interactive (headless) mode only**. The agent **must** run the corresponding CLI via the terminal (e.g. Cursor `Shell`) with the full prompt in the command line — **not** asking the user to paste into another app, and **not** using interactive TUI for automation.

| Tool | **Must use** | **Do not use for automation** |
|------|----------------|--------------------------------|
| Claude Code | `claude -p "…"` | Interactive `claude` without `-p` |
| OpenAI Codex | `codex exec "…"` | Interactive Codex TUI |
| Gemini CLI | `gemini -p "…"` | Interactive `gemini` |
| Qwen Code | `qwen -p "…"` | Interactive `qwen` |

**Note:** In Codex, `-p` is often **profile**, not print — use **`codex exec`** for non-interactive runs.

---

## B. CI / format / autofix — **also headless** (user requirement)

Any **mutating** or **fixer** work that changes files to unblock CI or satisfy linters **must** be executed **inside a headless wrapper**, not by the orchestrator running raw `pnpm` / `prettier` / `eslint --fix` / `ruff format` directly.

**Required pattern** (pick one executor; Claude Code is the default when unsure):

```text
claude -p --permission-mode bypassPermissions "cd <REPO_ROOT> && <exact shell commands, e.g. pnpm exec prettier --write path/to/file.md && git status>"
```

Use **`--permission-mode bypassPermissions`** on Claude Code when the inner commands need **Node / pnpm / npx** (see **§E**). If the executor is Codex, use **§F** default (**no Codex sandbox** — full permissions on trusted machines).

or (Codex — **default for this repo**, see **§F**):

```text
codex exec --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox "cd <REPO_ROOT> && <same commands>"
```

The orchestrator’s job is to **compose** the quoted string and **invoke** one such command via `Shell` — **not** to run `pnpm exec prettier --write ...` as the top-level command itself.

**Examples of “must wrap”:** `prettier --write`, `eslint --fix`, `ruff check --fix`, `ruff format`, any scripted apply that edits tracked files for CI green.

---

## C. What may still run **directly** (read-only / inspection)

These **do not** need a `claude -p` wrapper:

- **Read-only Git / GitHub**: `git status`, `git log`, `git diff` (no write), `gh run list`, `gh run view --log-failed`
- **Read-only verification** (no file writes): `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit`, `pnpm lint` **without** `--fix`, `pytest`, `vitest run` (assuming tests do not rewrite sources)

If a command might **write** files (including caches outside the rule’s intent), treat it as section **B**.

---

## D. Safety

- **`--permission-mode bypassPermissions`** is equivalent to **`--dangerously-skip-permissions`** (per Claude Code docs). Use **only** on a **trusted** dev machine / repo clone — never as a blanket habit for untrusted input.
- For locked-down automation (e.g. CI), prefer **`--permission-mode dontAsk`** plus explicit `permissions.allow` rules in Claude Code settings instead of bypass.

---

## E. Claude Code `-p` and **permission blocks** (pnpm / node / Bash)

**Symptom:** Headless `claude -p "…"` reports that **pnpm / npx / node** (or similar) is blocked by the permission system — non-interactive runs cannot click “Allow”.

**Cause:** Default permission modes require approval for many shell actions; `-p` has no interactive prompt, so execution stops or skips.

**Fix (trusted local — default for this workflow):** pass **`--permission-mode bypassPermissions`** together with **`-p`**:

```text
claude -p --permission-mode bypassPermissions "<single shell pipeline, e.g. cd repo/frontend && pnpm exec tsc --noEmit && pnpm lint && pnpm test>"
```

**Alternatives:**

| Goal | Flag / approach |
|------|------------------|
| Skip prompts; dev machine only | `--permission-mode bypassPermissions` or `--dangerously-skip-permissions` (same class — use sparingly) |
| Scripted / allowlist-only | `--permission-mode dontAsk` + narrow `permissions.allow` in Claude Code `settings.json` |
| No Claude involvement | Run `pnpm` / `uv` / `pytest` **outside** `claude -p` (orchestrator terminal only for read-only verify) |

**Docs (official):** [Permission modes](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permission-modes) · [Headless / non-interactive](https://code.claude.com/en/headless) · [Permissions](https://code.claude.com/en/permissions) · [Sandboxing](https://code.claude.com/en/sandboxing)

**Orchestrator behavior:** When composing a `claude -p` line that runs **pnpm/node**, **include** `--permission-mode bypassPermissions` in the same invocation unless the user forbids it or the environment is untrusted.

---

## F. Codex / Gemini / Qwen — **similar** issues (sandbox / approvals)

Headless runs **cannot** answer interactive prompts. Each tool uses different flags; **pnpm / npm / node** often need **write access** + **non-interactive approval** (or explicit auto-approve).

### OpenAI **Codex** (`codex exec`)

**Default (this repo — trusted local dev):** **do not use Codex sandbox** — give **full permissions** so `pnpm` / shell / tools are not blocked.

- **Use** `--dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox` **on every** `codex exec` the orchestrator composes (skips confirmation prompts and **does not** sandbox model-generated shell commands). See [CLI reference](https://developers.openai.com/codex/cli/reference/).
- **Do not** default to `-s read-only` or `-s workspace-write` here — those are for stricter or CI-style runs when you explicitly choose them.
- **Optional stricter modes** (only when you intentionally want sandboxing): `-s danger-full-access` | `workspace-write` | `read-only`, or `--full-auto` (workspace-write + on-request — still sandboxed).

**Docs:** [Sandboxing](https://developers.openai.com/codex/concepts/sandboxing/) · [CLI reference](https://developers.openai.com/codex/cli/reference/) · [Non-interactive (`codex exec`)](https://developers.openai.com/codex/noninteractive/)

**Example (default — trusted local):**

```text
codex exec --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox "cd e:/codespace/poco-claw/frontend && pnpm exec tsc --noEmit"
```

**Usage / rate limit:** If `codex exec` exits with an error mentioning **usage limit** (or equivalent quota / rate limit), **run the same command once more** after a short pause. If it fails again, stop and report to the user — do not loop indefinitely.

### **Gemini CLI** (`gemini -p`)

- **`--yolo` / `-y`**: auto-approve actions (per [headless docs](https://google-gemini.github.io/gemini-cli/docs/cli/headless.html)); combine with **`gemini -p "…"`** for automation when tools would otherwise need confirmation.
- **`--approval-mode`**: e.g. `auto_edit` (see same table in headless configuration options).
- **Sandboxing** is a **separate** layer (`-s` / `--sandbox`, `GEMINI_SANDBOX`, Docker/Seatbelt, etc.) — see [Sandboxing in the Gemini CLI](https://google-gemini.github.io/gemini-cli/docs/sandbox.html). If shell commands are blocked or isolated, adjust sandbox settings — not the same mechanism as Claude’s `bypassPermissions`.

#### **Clean headless output** (artifacts / logs)

YOLO lines, MCP startup, and skill override notices are typically written to **stderr**. **Do not** use **`2>&1`** when redirecting stdout to a file — that merges noise into the deliverable.

**Default for scripting:** **`--output-format json`**, drop stderr, then use **only** the **`response`** field (see [JSON output](https://google-gemini.github.io/gemini-cli/docs/cli/headless.html#json-output)).

**PowerShell (Windows):**

```text
$raw = Get-Content .\path\to\input.md -Raw | gemini -p "…" --approval-mode yolo --output-format json 2>$null
($raw | ConvertFrom-Json).response | Set-Content .\out.md -Encoding utf8
```

**jq (if available):**

```text
gemini -p "…" --approval-mode yolo --output-format json 2>$null | jq -r ".response" > out.md
```

Optional: set **`output.format`** to **`"json"`** in [settings.json](https://google-gemini.github.io/gemini-cli/docs/get-started/configuration.html) so scripts can omit the flag (applies to all runs — use only if acceptable).

### **Qwen Code** (`qwen -p`)

- **`--yolo` / `-y`** or **`--approval-mode yolo`**: auto-approve **edits and shell** — intended for **CI/CD and batch scripts** (see [Headless](https://qwenlm.github.io/qwen-code-docs/en/users/features/headless/) and [Approval mode](https://qwenlm.github.io/qwen-code-docs/en/users/features/approval-mode/)).
- Default / stricter modes in headless can **fail** when a tool needs approval and there is no interactive user — use **`yolo`** (or **auto-edit** if only file edits are auto-approved) for unattended runs.

**Example:**

```text
qwen -p --yolo "cd e:/codespace/poco-claw/frontend && pnpm exec tsc --noEmit"
```

### Orchestrator summary

| Tool | Typical “pnpm blocked / stuck” fix |
|------|-------------------------------------|
| Claude | `-p --permission-mode bypassPermissions` (§E) |
| Codex | **`--dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox`** (default — no Codex sandbox); usage limit → retry once (§F) |
| Gemini | `-p` + `--yolo` (or `auto_edit`) + **`--output-format json`** → **`.response`** only; **`2>$null`** — never `2>&1` into artifacts (§F Gemini) |
| Qwen | `-p` + `--yolo` or `--approval-mode yolo` |

All of these trade **safety** for **automation** — use only on **trusted** machines and repos.
